Based on my search results, here's what I found about getting the active sequence in **Premiere Pro's UXP API (2024/2025)**:

## Current Status

UXP (Unified Extensibility Platform) has officially graduated from beta and is now available in Adobe Premiere 25.6. As of November 2025, Premiere Pro has moved to extensibility based on UXP.(no content)If you are starting new development, start in UXP. CEP extensions continue to be supported; the plan is to support both CEP and UXP for a calendar year, after which they will remove support for CEP extensibility.

## Getting the Active Sequence in UXP

The correct approach to get the active sequence is:

```javascript
const ppro = require("premierepro");
const project = await ppro.Project.getActiveProject();
const sequence = await project.getActiveSequence();
```

Example from the forums showing how to retrieve the active sequence and its settings:

```javascript
const project = await ppro.Project.getActiveProject();
console.log("Project:", project);
const activeSequence = await project.getActiveSequence();
console.log("Active sequence:", activeSequence);
```

## Key Differences from ExtendScript

An important difference between ExtendScript (and CEP) and UXP in Premiere is that all ExtendScript calls to Premiere were synchronous and blocked the UI while executing. In UXP, method calls are asynchronous and do not block the UI thread. For a smooth transition, all properties (get and set) in the API were designed to be synchronous and do not need to be awaited.

## Working with Selection in Active Sequence

You can also get the selection from the active sequence using `getSelection()` and bind to events:

```javascript
app.bind("onActiveSequenceSelectionChanged", function () {
    const selection = app.project.activeSequence.getSelection();
    // ...
});
```

## Resources

- The Premiere Pro UXP API documentation is available at: https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/
- The Project class documentation shows static methods like `getActiveProject` for getting the currently active project.
- Sample plugins are available at: https://github.com/AdobeDocs/uxp-premiere-pro-samples

## Known Issues

Some developers have reported issues where `app.project` returns undefined when using the older `new Application()` approach. The recommended approach is to use `ppro.Project.getActiveProject()` as shown above.


